e enable for the tens digit is `(d0 == 9)`. The enable for the hundreds digit is `(d1 == 9 && d0 == 9)`. \n    - Let's check the testbench `ena_ref`. The testbench uses `ena_ref` and `q_ref`. In a standard 4-digit BCD counter, `q` increments every cycle. `ena` is used to signal the carry.\n    - Let's implement: `d0` increments every cycle. `d1` increments if `d0 == 9`. `d2` increments if `d1 == 9 && d0 == 9`. `d3` increments if `d2 == 9 && d1 == 9 && d0 == 9`. \n    - `ena[0]` is `(d0 == 9)`, `ena[1]` is `(d1 == 9 && d0 == 9)`, `ena[2]` is `(d2 == 9 && d1 == 9 && d0 == 9)`. \n4. **Advice to avoid syntax errors**:\n    - Ensure all ports are declared with types (logic).\n    - Use `always @(*)` for combinational logic to avoid sensitivity list errors.\n    - Use non-blocking assignments `<= ` for sequential logic.\n    - Ensure the bit-width of concatenation `{d3, d2, d1, d0}` matches the 16-bit output `q`.",
    "module": "module TopModule(\n    input  logic       clk,\n    input  logic       reset,\n    output logic [2:0] ena,\n    output logic [15:0] q\n);\n\n    logic [3:0] d0, d1, d2, d3;\n\n    // Sequential logic for BCD digits\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        if (reset) begin\n            d0 <= 4'b0000;\n            d1 <= 4'b0000;\n            d2 <= 4'b0000;\n            d3 <= 4'b0000;\n        end else begin\n            // Ones digit increments every cycle\n            if (d0 == 4'd9) {\n                d0 <= 4'd0;\n                // Tens digit increments if ones is 9\n                if (d1 == 4'd9) {\n                    d1 <= 4'd0;\n                    // Hundreds digit increments if tens is 9 and ones is 9\n                    if (d2 == 4'd9) {\n                        d2 <= 4'd0;\n                        // Thousands digit increments if hundreds is 9 and tens is 9 and ones is 9\n                        if (d3 == 4'd9) {\n                            d3 <= 4'd0;\n                        } else begin\n                            d3 <= d3 + 4'd1;\n                        end\n                    } else begin\n                        d2 <= d2 + 4'd1;\n                    end\n                } else begin\n                    d1 <= d1 + 4'd1;\n                end\n            } else begin\n                d0 <= d0 + 4'd1;\n            end\n        end\n    end\n\n    // The logic above is a bit nested. Let's use a cleaner approach for BCD incrementing.\n    // Standard BCD counter logic:\n    // d0 increments every clock.\n    // d1 increments if d0 == 9.\n    // d2 increments if d1 == 9 and d0 == 9.\n    // d3 increments if d2 == 9 and d1 == 9 and d0 == 9.\n\n    // Let's rewrite the sequential block for clarity and correctness.\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        if (reset) begin\n            d0 <= 4'd0;\n            d1 <= 4'd0;\n            d2 <= 4'd0;\n            d3 <= 4'd0;\n        end else begin\n            // Ones digit\n            if (d0 == 4'd9) d0 <= 4'd0;\n            else            d0 <= d0 + 4'd1;\n\n            // Tens digit\n            if (d0 == 4'd9) begin\n                if (d1 == 4'd9) d1 <= 4'd0;\n                else            d1 <= d1 + 4'd1;\n            end\n\n            // Hundreds digit\n            if (d0 == 4'd9 && d1 == 4'd9) begin\n                if (d2 == 4'd9) d2 <= 4'd0;\n                else            d2 <= d2 + 4'd1;\n            end\n\n            // Thousands digit\n            if (d0 == 4'd9 && d1 == 4'd9 && d2 == 4'd9) begin\n                if (d3 == 4'd9) d3 <= 4'd0;\n                else            d3 <= d3 + 4'd1;\n            end\n        end\n    end\n\n    // Combinational logic for enable signals\n    // ena[0] is enable for d1 (tens)\n    // ena[1] is enable for d2 (hundreds)\n    // ena[2] is enable for d3 (thousands)\n    always @(*) begin\n        ena[0] = (d0 == 4'd9);\n        ena[1] = (d0 == 4'd9 && d1 == 4'd9);\n        ena[2] = (d0 == 4'd9 && d1 == 4'd9 && d2 == 4'd9);\n    end\n\n    // Combinational logic for output q\n    assign q = {d3, d2, d1, d0};\n\nendmodule"
